Heatmaps of KDA¶

Lets create a DataFrame to analyze kills, death and assists (KDA).

In [ ]:
r_kills = ['r{0}_kills'.format(i) for i in range(1,6)]
r_deaths = ['r{0}_deaths'.format(i) for i in range(1,6)]
r_assists = ['r{0}_assists'.format(i) for i in range(1,6)]
r_kda = r_kills+r_deaths+r_assists

d_kills = ['d{0}_kills'.format(i) for i in range(1,6)]
d_deaths = ['d{0}_deaths'.format(i) for i in range(1,6)]
d_assists = ['d{0}_assists'.format(i) for i in range(1,6)]
d_kda = d_kills+d_deaths+d_assists

kda_feat_df = df_train_features[r_kda+d_kda].copy()
kda_feat_df['target'] = target

kda_feat_df['r_tot_kills'] = kda_feat_df[r_kills].sum(axis=1)
kda_feat_df['r_tot_deaths'] = kda_feat_df[r_deaths].sum(axis=1)
kda_feat_df['r_tot_assists'] = kda_feat_df[r_assists].sum(axis=1)

kda_feat_df['d_tot_kills'] = kda_feat_df[d_kills].sum(axis=1)
kda_feat_df['d_tot_deaths'] = kda_feat_df[d_deaths].sum(axis=1)
kda_feat_df['d_tot_assists'] = kda_feat_df[d_assists].sum(axis=1)

tot_cols = ['r_tot_kills', 'r_tot_deaths', 'r_tot_assists', 'd_tot_kills', 'd_tot_deaths', 'd_tot_assists']

display(kda_feat_df.sample(3))

KDA in dota is calculated as: (K+A)/D

In [ ]:
kda_feat_df['r_kda'] = (kda_feat_df['r_tot_kills']+kda_feat_df['r_tot_assists'])/kda_feat_df['r_tot_deaths']
kda_feat_df['d_kda'] = (kda_feat_df['d_tot_kills']+kda_feat_df['d_tot_assists'])/kda_feat_df['d_tot_deaths']

Learning a CatBoost Classification model¶

In [ ]:
X = df_train_features
y = df_train_targets['radiant_win']
X_test = df_test_features
y_cat = pd.Series(df_train_targets['radiant_win'].map({True: 1, False: 0})) #catboost doesn't understand True,False 
n_fold = 5
folds = KFold(n_splits=n_fold, shuffle=True, random_state=11)
cv = ShuffleSplit(n_splits=n_fold, test_size=0.3, random_state=17)
In [ ]:
X_train, X_valid, y_train, y_valid = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=17)
In [ ]:
model = CatBoostClassifier(iterations=400,random_seed=42,eval_metric='AUC',logging_level='Silent', loss_function='Logloss')
In [ ]:
%%time
model.fit(X_train, y_train,
    eval_set=(X_valid, y_valid),
    plot=True
);

Let's try doing Cross Validation

In [ ]:
%%time
cv_params = model.get_params()
print('cv params: ', cv_params)
pool = Pool(X, y)

cv_data = cv(
    pool,
    cv_params,
    fold_count=5,
    plot=True,
    seed=17
)

cv params:  {'iterations': 400, 'loss_function': 'Logloss', 'random_seed': 42, 'logging_level': 'Silent', 'eval_metric': 'AUC'}

In [ ]:
print('Best validation accuracy score: {:.2f}±{:.4f} on step {}'.format(
    np.max(cv_data['test-AUC-mean']),
    cv_data['test-AUC-std'][np.argmax(cv_data['test-AUC-mean'])],
    np.argmax(cv_data['test-AUC-mean'])
))

Best validation accuracy score: 0.80±0.0053 on step 398

An AUC score of 0.80 is typically regarded as favorable, indicating that the classifier effectively distinguishes between positive and negative classes with a strong level of separability.

Furthermore, the narrow standard deviation of ±0.0053 implies that the model consistently performs well across various iterations or subsets of the data, highlighting its robustness and reliability.

The model demonstrated a robust performance, achieving an AUC score of 0.80±0.0053. This high score means my CatBoost model was able to distinguish between wins and losses quite accurately. While this result is promising, I will continue to refine my model to enhance its predictive power further, aiming to provide Dota 2 players and enthusiasts with a reliable tool for predicting match outcomes.
